  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "DARREN  POGIR",
    "text": "Hi. I'm Darren. And speaking on behalf of the grandchildren, I'd just like to say what a wonderful man Motel has been. He's had the strength to be able to sit at Friday night supper with us and tell us about his experiences and stories. And we've gained from all of this, because I feel that the youth today aren't really in touch with all that happened. Not that we can really feel his pain, but it's been a great experience to hear all the stories. And on behalf of all of us, I'd just like to thank him. I think he's a wonderful man, with great strength and courage, and a man I'll always look up to and remember for the rest of my life. And while we're on tape, I just want to thank him. And we all love him. And he's a wonderful man. And I'd just talk to make a mention to Ida, who's not here with us today, that she definitely isn't forgotten. We think of her on a regular basis. We love her. She was with Motel through these terrible times. And she also had the strength to pull Motel through and to bring up two [? also ?] beautiful sons that have given us opportunities. And thanks to her and Motel. And we love them both. Thanks. [PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS] JOY (DAUGHTER-IN-LAW): As a daughter-in-law, having been in the family for many years, I must say the stories we've heard are very important for the future generations who won't be able to hear these first-hand. And these tapes are very important to ensure that we remember everything. It must never be forgotten. And we must make sure it never happens again.",
